'''Alain Kaleta Olony T. Kashama''' is a professional [[Canadian football]] [[defensive end]] for the [[Calgary Stampeders]] of the [[Canadian Football League]]. He was signed by the [[Chicago Bears]] as an [[undrafted free agent]] in 2004. He played [[college football]] for the [[Michigan Wolverines football|Michigan Wolverines]].

Kashama has also played for the [[Seattle Seahawks]], [[Montreal Alouettes]] and [[Hamilton Tiger-Cats]].

==College career==
Kashama attended the [[University of Michigan]] where he majored in [[African-American]] studies.<ref name="Slam!">{{cite news|url=http://www.canoe.ca/NFLCanadaNews04/0722.html|title=Montreal's Alain Kashama Among the Canadians Battling For Roster Spots As Training Camp Begins|date=July 22, 2004|publisher=Slam! Sports|accessdate=2009-07-01}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> He played in 40 games, starting six<ref name="Slam!" /> for the [[Michigan Wolverines|Wolverines]] [[Michigan Wolverines football|football team]].<ref name="French Two">{{cite news|url=http://www2.canoe.com/sports/nouvelles/archives/2007/06/20070620-113400.html|title=Alain Kashama a les outils pour devenir un partant|date=June 20, 2007|publisher=Canoe.ca|language=French|accessdate=2009-07-01}}</ref> In those games Kashama recorded a grand total of 48 [[Tackle (football move)|tackles]] and six [[Quarterback sack|sacks]].<ref name="French Two" /> During his first three years at Michigan, Kashama was mainly a backup [[defensive end]] playing in pass rushing downs and when others were injured.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/football/article.aspx?id=38738|title=Michigan Player Comments Previewing Houston|date=September 1, 2003|publisher=Michigan Wolverines|accessdate=2009-07-01}}</ref> However, after [[Shantee Orr]] declared for the [[2003 NFL Draft]], Kashama was expected to start as a senior.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.michigandaily.com/content/orrs-decision-leave-should-not-bother-fans|title=Orr's decision to leave should not bother fans|last=Smith|first=Joe|date=January 16, 2003|publisher=The Michigan Daily|accessdate=2009-07-01}}</ref>

==Professional career==
===Chicago Bears===
After going undrafted in the [[2004 NFL Draft]], Kashama signed with the [[Chicago Bears]] on April 26, 2004.<ref name="BaltSun">{{cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/topic/cs-2004howthebearswerebuilt,0,7785279.story?page=2|title=How the 2004 Bears were built|date=September 8, 2004|publisher=The Baltimore Sun|accessdate=2009-07-01}}</ref> After his signing, the Bears were reportedly starting to, "envision ways in which Kashama could contribute if he keeps improving at his current rate."<ref name="Tribune">{{cite news|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/678970611.html?dids=678970611:678970611&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Aug+16%2C+2004&author=DAVID+HAUGH&pub=Chicago+Tribune&desc=Bears+doing+flips+over+Michigan+rookie+end&pqatl=google|title=Bears doing flips over Michigan rookie end|last=Haugh|first=David|date=August 16, 2004|publisher=Chicago Tribune|accessdate=2009-07-01}}</ref> He played in three games for Chicago before being traded to the [[Seattle Seahawks]].<ref name="Stamps">{{cite web|url=http://www.stampeders.com/team/player_roster/career/?id=176|title=#97 Alain Kashama|publisher=Calgary Stampeders|accessdate=2009-07-01}}</ref>

===Seattle Seahawks===
After being traded to the Seahawks, Kashama played in one game with Seattle before the Seahawks released him on July 31, 2006.<ref name="TiCats">{{cite web|url=http://www.ticats.ca/roster/show/id/972|title=#77 Alain Kashama|publisher=Hamilton Tiger-Cats Football Club|accessdate=2009-07-01}}</ref>

===Montreal Alouettes===
Kashama was drafted by the [[Montreal Alouettes]] in the [[2004 CFL Draft]] but opted to sign with the [[National Football League|NFL]]'s [[Chicago Bears]].<ref name="French Two" /> In 2007, Kashama led Montreal in [[Quarterback sacks|sacks]]<ref name="French One">{{cite news|url=http://www2.canoe.com/sports/nouvelles/football/alouettes/archives/2009/02/20090223-193745.html|title=Alain Kashama quitte les Alouettes|date=February 23, 2009|publisher=Canoe.ca|language=French|accessdate=2009-07-01}}</ref> with eight.<ref name="CFL">{{cite web|url=http://www.cfl.ca/index.php/roster/show/id/972|title=CFL.ca bio|publisher=Canadian Football League|accessdate=2009-07-01}}</ref> Kashama also recorded 29 [[Tackle (football move)|tackles]] for the Alouettes.<ref name="TiCats Trade">{{cite news|url=http://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/?id=3716513|title=Ticats Acquire Alain Kashama|date=September 10, 2008|publisher=Our Sports Central|accessdate=2009-07-01}}</ref> On July 21, 2008, it was reported by ''[[The Montreal Gazette]]'' that Kashama was to be traded after suffering a [[knee]] injury. [[Jim Popp]], the Alouettes [[general manager]] shot down the rumors of a possible trade although he didn't deny that teams such as the [[Calgary Stampeders]] and [[Edmonton Eskimos]] were calling.<ref name="French 3">{{cite news|url=http://www.rds.ca/alouettes/chroniques/256129.html|title=Kashama fait encore partie des plans|date=July 21, 2008|publisher=RDS.ca|language=French|accessdate=2009-07-01}}</ref>

===Hamilton Tiger-Cats===
Kashama was traded to the [[Hamilton Tiger-Cats]] on September 10, 2008, for a conditional pick in the [[2009 CFL Draft]].<ref name="TiCats Trade" /> With Hamilton he recorded five tackles and one sack.<ref name="TiCats" /><ref name="CFL" />

===Calgary Stampeders===
On February 24, 2009, Kashama signed with the [[Calgary Stampeders]].<ref name="French One" />

==Personal==
Kashama was born on December 8, 1979, in the [[Democratic Republic of Congo]] before moving to [[Brampton, Ontario]] and then [[Montreal, Quebec]] as a child.<ref name="Slam!" /><ref name="French Two" /> Because of this move, Kashama is now fluent in French.<ref name="Slam!" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/football/article.aspx?id=39656|title=Player Comments from Weekly U-M Football Media Luncheon|date=September 30, 2002|publisher=University of Michigan|accessdate=2009-07-01}}</ref> He played [[high school football]] at [[Vieux Montreal]], and recorded over 200 tackles and 50 sacks while being ranked as the second best prep player in [[Canada]].<ref name="Slam!" /> During high school, Kashama also played [[basketball]] and ran [[Track & Field|track]].<ref name="Wolverines">{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/football/playerbio.aspx?id=112706|title=#95 Alain Kashama|publisher=University of Michigan|accessdate=2009-07-01}}</ref> His brother [[Fernand Kashama|Fernand]] is his teammate with Calgary while his cousin [[Tim Biakabutuka]] was a [[running back]] for the [[Carolina Panthers]]. His brother [[Hakeem Kashama|Hakeem]] also played professional football with the [[Hamilton Tiger-Cats]].<ref name="Stamps" /> He credits his cousin for getting him interested in football and said that, "I started to play football after he was drafted in 1996."<ref name="French Two" /> Kashama is nicknamed "Sackmaster" by his teammates.<ref name="Slam!" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.michigandaily.com/node/37506|title='Sackmaster' finally makes impact|last=McCollough|first=J. Brady|date=September 30, 2002|publisher=The Michigan Daily|accessdate=2009-07-01}}</ref>

